<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JAN 92 / Japanese banks change strategy: Institute Of Geographers
Conference
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JAPANESE BANKS in the UK are behaving increasingly like other foreign and
British banks in Britain, the Institute of British Geographers' Conference
in Swansea was told yesterday.
Their lending patterns are starting to resemble those of other banks, said
Mr Adam Tickell, a researcher at Leeds University.
By late last year there were nine Japanese banks with offices outside London
with a total of 26 employees, and 53 banks in the capital with almost 4,000
employees. Japanese banks make up the second-largest concentration of
foreign banks in the UK after those from the US.
The banks moved into the regions in response to lower rents, because of a
desire to make contact with customers outside London, and to follow the
growing importance of regional centres with strong banking presences. The
banks typically said that 50 per cent of their loans went to Japanese
businesses in the UK.
When the banks started in the UK in the mid-1980s, they focused on loans to
the distribution sector, where there was a Japanese presence. However, the
balance of their portfolios now closely resembles lending by other banks.
About 40 per cent of outstanding loans last August were to financial
services companies, with 18 per cent to distribution companies and 18 per
cent to construction and property companies.
Lending by Japanese banks represents 7.5 per cent of all UK resident
lending, defined as lending to domestic organisations.
If London's role as an international financial centre declines and the
Japanese banks move abroad, it could have a fundamental impact on British
business, he said.
</TEXT>
