<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JAN 92 / UK News (Employment): Stress 'not just bosses' disease'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JOB STRESS is at least as high among blue-collar workers as it is among
executives, the annual occupational psychology conference of the British
Psychological Society was told yesterday.
A study of stress and sickness absence among managers and shopfloor workers
at Scottish and Newcastle Breweries in Edinburgh showed that job stress was
not just a 'bosses' disease', Dr Rosalind Bramwell and Professor Cary Cooper
from the University of Manchester Institute of Science and Technology told
the conference.
Prof Cooper said that companies were often mistakenly concentrating on
white-collar groups when it came to measures to reduce stress. Failure to
recognise stress among manual groups 'must be costing British industry a
fortune in lost working days', he said.
The study found that shopfloor workers were taking 2 1/2 times as many days
off sick compared as their managerial colleagues. Much of the time off could
be linked to stress arising from a sense of being poorly valued, said the
researchers.
Questionnaires were sent to more than 600 employees, from directors to
clerical workers and draymen. Rates of sickness absence were taken from the
brewery's records.
A warning to companies to beware of 'cowboy' publishers of personality and
aptitude tests was made at the conference by Dr Rob Feltham, director of
test publishers ASE.
Tests at the 'cheap and dirty end' of the market ran the risk of being
biased against, for example, Asian and Afro-Caribbean job applicants, he
said.
</TEXT>
