<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JAN 92 / Pressure for changes to accountancy institute
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CHARTERED ACCOUNTANTS are pressing their main professional body to change
fundamentally the way it operates by dividing in two.
A group of members of the Institute of Chartered Accountants in England and
Wales is calling for a separate body to represent members' interests,
alongside the institute's role of upholding professional standards.
A paper has been circulated to district societies and members of the
institute's council, its ruling body. It argues that the institute cannot
fulfil both functions and calls on it to establish a new organisation with
salaried directors to offer commercial services such as indemnity insurance,
and to lobby on behalf of the profession. The council's annual conference
begins today.
The charter of the institute, the paper says, restricts its activities to
advancing the profession rather than the interests of its members. These do
not coincide and raise questions of a conflict of interest.
Mr John Butcher, a sole practitioner and a supporter of the campaign for
change, said: 'There is growing concern that the institute has difficulty in
fulfilling both roles. The question is whether there can be reform without
generating bad feeling. But we are not prepared to be ignored.'
A more detailed paper on the subject will be submitted to the council by the
start of next month. If there was no sign of change by April, Mr Butcher
said there might be a move to 'make our views known at a special meeting'.
He said the ideas covered a 'broad cross-section of the profession,
including people in positions of influence'.
The move comes after more than a year of discussions over the future of the
institute since some of its regulatory functions were transferred to the
independent Accounting Standards Board.
</TEXT>
