<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JAN 92 / Ravenscraig to close with 1,200 job cuts
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JAMES BUXTON, CHARLES LEADBEATER and ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH STEEL yesterday sounded the death knell for steelmaking in Scotland
by announcing it would close its Ravenscraig complex in Lanarkshire by
September with the loss of 1,200 jobs.
Mr John Major, the prime minister, said he wished the company had been able
to meet a pledge it gave in 1987 to keep the plant open until 1994, while Mr
Neil Kinnock, the Labour leader, accused the government of walking away from
the people of Lanarkshire.
The plant's future has been in doubt since last year when its hot strip
rolling mill was closed with the loss of 700 jobs.
The area around the plant has been hit by almost 4,000 steel-related job
losses in the past two years and unemployment is expected to climb to almost
20 per cent.
People in nearby Motherwell and workers at the plant reacted with sombre
resignation to the news of the closure.
The government responded to the closure by announcing that it had decided to
designate Lanarkshire as a special enterprise zone and was seeking the
necessary European Commission agreement to the move. Businesses setting up
on these specified sites will avoid rates and corporation tax for a 10 year
period.
Setting up the zone will involve spending about Pounds 50m in addition to
the extra Pounds 15m the government is spending in north Lanarkshire this
year and Pounds 25m pledged for next year.
Mr Ian Lang, the Scottish secretary, said it should secure 7,500 new jobs in
the area over 10 years.
The Ravenscraig plant has been politically controversial since 1959 when the
Conservative Macmillan government decided it should be developed to form the
hub of a manufacturing area making ships and vehicles.
Despite investment of more than Pounds 400m in the 1970s, when the complex
employed 13,000, Ravenscraig has been vulnerable to closure throughout the
past decade.
The closure is British Steel's most aggressive response yet to the UK
recession. It is likely to make a loss of between Pounds 80m and Pounds 100m
this year as a result of lower steel demand, increasing competition from
imports and a steep fall in prices over the past two years.
The company also disclosed that the recession had forced it to postpone
plans for a Pounds 100m investment in a continuous casting machine at its
Llanwern plant in South Wales. The plan to expand Llanwern's capacity was
one of the main justifications the company gave in 1990 for the closure of
the Ravenscraig hot strip mill.
The main steel plant left in Scotland, the Dalzell plate mill, has had a
question-mark over its future since last July when the company announced it
planned to build a new plate mill at Lackenby on Teesside, in north-east
England.
The Hunterston deep sea port will also be closed with the loss of about 50
jobs.
Mr Lang said British Steel's decision was 'hugely disappointing' though it
could not have come as a complete surprise to anyone aware of the recent
steep fall in British Steel's profits.
He said he had pressed Sir Robert Scholey, the British Steel chairman, to
make public his assessment of market conditions which justified breaking his
undertaking to keep Ravenscraig open until 1994.
Trade union leaders at the plant reacted with resignation to the closure.
'There was an inevitability about it,' said Mr Willie Twaddle, senior works
convener at the plant, 'even though we were guaranteed to 1994.'
Mr Donald Dewar, shadow Scottish secretary, said the closure was the result
of 'British Steel's misjudgment and malice compounded by an abdication of
all responsibility by this government'.
