<DATE>920109
</DATE>
<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JAN 92 / Bank poised to step in as sterling slides
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By PETER MARSH, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE BANK of England went on alert last night after sterling ended the day
within a whisker of its lowest permitted point in the European exchange rate
mechanism and at its weakest close against the D-Mark since the UK entered
the ERM 15 months ago.
Should the pound continue to fall and intervention by the Bank fail to stop
the slide, Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, faces the politically damaging
option of having to raise interest rates to increase sterling's value.
Such a move would threaten the fragile UK recovery, and lead to more calls
from Conservative backbenchers and anti-ERM economists for a sterling
devaluation - an option which the government has ruled out.
After a nervous day on currency and equity markets, sterling closed in
London down a pfennig at DM2.8350, within roughly a quarter of a pfennig of
its effective ERM floor of about DM2.8325.
In late New York trading it fluctuated around the same level, at one point
falling to DM2.832.
Sterling's weakness was caused largely by a stronger D-Mark and lack of
support from investors worried by signs of a long and slow recovery from the
UK recession.
On the London stock market, share prices suffered from concern about the
world economy and reports of President Bush's collapse. However, the FT-SE
100 index of leading shares recovered from a 41-point loss to close at
2,467.0, down 15.9.
The mood on markets was one of edgy calm. 'There is a marked absence of good
news,' said Mr Mark Brett, currency analyst at Barclays de Zoete Wedd, a
London investment bank.
Assuming sterling opens today weaker, Mr Lamont is thought likely to
instruct the Bank to buy sterling on foreign exchange markets, rather than
risk the much more unpalatable option of increasing interest rates from
their current 10.5 per cent.
If the pound hits its ERM floor, intervention by the Bank would probably be
aided by similar moves by other European central banks to push up sterling's
value.
Also, since the pound's lower effective limit in the ERM is set by the
peseta, the strongest currency in the system, the Bank of Spain would be
called on to sell the Spanish currency, cutting its value and reducing the
pressure on the UK unit.
Should large-scale intervention be required, however, a question mark hangs
over the readiness of the other ERM members to lend wholehearted support.
Since the Bundesbank increased German interest rates just before Christmas,
all the other countries, except Britain, have increased borrowing rates
because of the strains in the mechanism. These nations might argue that the
UK should do likewise, as part of the learning process associated with
joining the ERM.
Economic Viewpoint, Page 17
Lex, Page 18
Currencies, Page 27
World stocks, Page 33
London stocks, Page 36
</TEXT>
