FT  09 JAN 92 / International Company News: Foreign exchange activity lifts
Banca del Gottardo
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By IAN RODGER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   ZURICH
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
NET PROFIT of Banca del Gottardo, the Lugano-based Swiss bank in which
Japan's Sumitomo Bank has a majority stake, rose 9.5 per cent to SFr46m
(Dollars 33m) in 1991, thanks to strong activity in foreign exchange
business, a satisfactory trend in interest margins and exceptional
contributions from recent acquisitions.
The directors proposed maintaining the 20 per cent dividend, equal to SFr20
per share or participation certificate.
Cash-flow was up 34 per cent to SFr110m. The bank was thus able to carry on
with its policy of depreciating new investments and covering exposure
towards risk countries. Provisions and depreciation allowances were up 60
per cent to SFr64m. The bank said that difficulties in the Swiss property
market had only a 'minor' impact.
Total assets rose 8 per cent to SFr7.4bn.
Despite a decline in the number of its subsidiaries, the bank estimates that
its consolidated net profit will exceed 1990's SFr51m.
