<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JAN 92 / Proposal on financial reinsurance
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FINANCIAL reinsurance, the policies taken out to protect financial
transactions, should be treated like conventional reinsurance in company
accounts only if there is a transfer of risk, the Institute of Chartered
Accountants in England and Wales has recommended in a discussion paper.
Financial reinsurance is unlike conventional reinsurance because sometimes
there is no transfer of risk, and the policy is often written so that it is
likely claims will be made within a predetermined range.
If the reinsurer assumes a proportion of exposure to the future losses of
the company taking out the policy, and the underwriting margin or deficit is
not fixed in advance, premiums should be charged against underwriting
revenue, the institute says.
Otherwise - where financial reinsurance is essentially a financing
arrangement - it should be accounted for as a cash deposit and any amounts
repayable treated as a liability.
The paper is a response to proposals that will soon be converted into a
financial reporting standard.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 6
</PAGE>
