<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JAN 92 / Chemicals output set to lift 2%
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DANIEL GREEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CHEMICALS manufacturing will grow by 2 per cent this year but investment
will continue to decline sharply, falling 6 per cent compared with 15 per
cent last year, said Mr Richard Freeman, Imperial Chemical Industries' chief
economist, yesterday.
Any improvement in output will come after a stagnant 1991 and, with most of
the gain expected in the second half of this year, is in line with forecasts
for much of the rest of British manufacturing.
Demand for chemicals will rise a little faster than GDP, accompanied by a 3
1/2 per cent growth in imports, compared with one per cent last year. Export
growth will slow slightly from 3 1/2 per cent to 3 per cent, said Mr Freeman
at the annual business outlook conference of the UK Chemical Industries
Association.
The UK's performance will be in line with that of the chemicals industry in
the rest of Europe, in spite of a halving of demand for chemicals products
in Germany.
The star performer in the UK last year, for the second year running, was the
pharmaceuticals sector. 'Without pharmaceuticals, chemical production in
1991 would have fallen by 2 per cent,' said Mr Freeman, who chairs the
association's economic appraisal committee. Drugs output will grow by 4 per
cent this year, he forecast.
Fertiliser production will continue to fall, he said, but the forecast of a
1 per cent fall is still a sharp improvement on last year's decline of 9 per
cent.
Fertiliser production has fallen over a number of years. Sales depend on a
number of factors outside market forces such as environmental pressures and
the European Community's Common Agricultural Policy.
UK production of inorganic chemicals will recover after last year's fall in
volume of more than 10 per cent. This was exaggerated by the gradual
abandonment of chlorofluorocarbons, the coolant used in refrigerators that
is blamed for damaging the ozone layer.
Production of CFC replacements had not yet taken up the shortfall and
inorganic output will recover by only 2 per cent this year.
Demand for organic chemicals was soft. Growth is expected to fall from 5 per
cent last year to 2 per cent this year as rising exports offset some of the
inroads made by imports.
The association warned that some of the government statistics used were
unreliable, and any revisions would probably be downward. It is seeking a
meeting with the Central Statistical Office to discuss the matter.
</TEXT>
