<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JAN 92 / Finnish PM tries to calm debate on EC entry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ROBERT TAYLOR
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   STOCKHOLM
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
FINLAND'S centre-right coalition is to publish a document today setting out
the arguments for and against joining the European Community. However, Mr
Esko Aho, the country's prime minister, is urging his own Centre party not
to take an early public stance on whether Finland should apply. His appeal
reflects a split inside the party over the issue.
The government's document, which ministers hope will stimulate a national
public debate, is to be discussed in parliament on Monday, but the
government is not expected to make a decision until next month at the
earliest, and possibly not until the spring.
What that decision is will depend largely on the attitude of the Centre
party, which is the largest in Mr Aho's four-party coalition. Centre has won
support in urban areas but its traditional power base remains central and
northern Finland where it reflects the interests of farmers, many of whom
remain hostile to, or sceptical about, the EC.
Mr Aho had appeared in recent months to be moving towards support for an EC
application. The Conservatives - the second largest party in his coalition -
want an early government declaration in support of EC entry, as have the
main opposition Social Democrats. Finland's main employers' associations and
national trade union organisations are also backing EC membership.
Registered unemployment in Finland rose to 9.8 per cent in November, for a
total of 243,000 people. This is the highest jobless total ever recorded in
the country.
