<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JAN 92 / EC observers seek part in helicopter inquiry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   BELGRADE
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
EUROPEAN Community monitors want to be involved in the inquiry set up by the
Yugoslav military after federal army jets shot down an EC helicopter on
Tuesday afternoon, killing five people, diplomats said yesterday.
At the same time, the 170 EC monitors, most of them based in Zagreb, the
Croatian capital, have temporarily suspended their activities until they
obtain guarantees of security.
The suspension means that a trilateral meeting aimed at shoring up the
ceasefire in Croatia has been postponed. Today's negotiations in Pecs in
Hungary would have involved EC monitors, the Croatian government and the
federal army, the Hungarian foreign ministry said.
Mr Joao de Silva, the monitor's spokesman in Zagreb, said the mission was
waiting to hold talks with federal army representatives who failed to turn
up at a meeting scheduled for yesterday morning.
'At this meeting we want to know the exact circumstances of what happened. .
. . and obtain the necessary guarantees to let our monitors perform their
job,' he told Croatian radio. 'The activities of our monitors are
interrupted until we obtain these guarantees.'
Western diplomats in Belgrade are concerned that the federal army, led by
General Veljko Kadiejevic, the defence minister, will try to keep the
inquiry internal. They said the investigation must establish who issued the
instructions to shoot down the helicopter, and to fire the missiles.
The federal army has described the incident as 'tragic', and Colonel Zvonka
Jurjevic, head of the air force, and a Croat, was suspended.
However, an article in Polityka, the Belgrade newspaper, regarded as a
mouthpiece for the Serbian government, said the two helicopters involved in
the incident did not have clearance to fly the last leg of their journey
from the Hungarian border to Zagreb. The helicopter had been shot down
because it was operating in closed air-space.
Mr Dobrosav Veizovic, Serbia's deputy foreign minister, told the BBC that in
the past, two helicopters had been using this air corridor for 'the illegal
importation of arms to Croatia. . . . that is one of the reasons which might
be the cause (for the attack on the helicopter).'
But a senior western diplomat said: 'If the army thinks it can blame the EC
for this accident, or try to cover up in any way, it is mistaken. This
accident confirms why the army must be brought under political control as
quickly as possible.'
Italy yesterday said the attack on the helicopter pointed to a deliberate
attempt to scupper international efforts to end the fighting in Yugoslavia.
An EC peace conference on Yugoslavia is due to resume in Brussels today as
planned.
</TEXT>
