<HEADLINE>
FT  09 JAN 92 / Monitoring role of EC's 'ice-cream men' crucial
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
CALLED the ice-cream men by their supporters, but lackeys of Germany by
their opponents, the white-uniformed EC observers have played a crucial role
in trying to monitor 15 ceasefires since arriving in Croatia last August.
The 170 unarmed monitors have worked indefatigably from their headquarters
in Hotel 'I' in Zagreb. Moreover, because this is the first time that the EC
has sent monitors to any country, they have had no previous experience or
standards to adopt.
Their task initially was to supervise the implementation of ceasefires
forged by the EC with the federal army, Croatia's national guard, and Serb
and Croat paramilitary units.
But, since September, the monitors have been involved in setting up
negotiations to secure the peaceful withdrawal of soldiers from federal army
garrisons in Croatia.
In addition, the monitors set up many local ceasefires to secure the safe
passage of relief and medical supplies, and some reprieve from the war for
civilians. Above all, the monitors have attempted to set up
confidence-building measures.
'It has not been easy. We have been manipulated by Croats, Serbs, and the
federal army. We have been shot at, our helicopters were fired on in the
autumn, but we feel we have made substantial progress. We must continue,'
said one Zagreb-based monitor.
</TEXT>
