<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JAN 92 / Gunmen fire on supporters of Gamsakhurdia
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By AGENCIES
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   TBILISI
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
GUNMEN loyal to Georgia's new military council yesterday opened fire on
several thousand people staging a rally in support of ousted President Zviad
Gamsakhurdia, agencies report from Tbilisi. Several people were believed to
have been wounded.
It was the second time gunmen had fired on peaceful pro-Gamsakhurdia
demonstrators. Last Friday, at least two people were killed and 25 wounded
when men opened fire with machine guns on a rally held in defiance of the
ban on public demonstrations.
The latest violence came as Georgian rebels seeking the extradition of Mr
Gamsakhurdia were reported to be holding talks on his fate with Armenia,
where he has taken refuge. A local journalist said the two sides began
negotiations in the Armenian border town of Idzhevan, where Mr Gamsakhurdia
fled with 120 of his supporters on Monday.
Mr Georgy Chanturia, leader of the opposition National Democratic Party,
accused Mr Gamsakhurdia's men of killing and torturing prisoners during the
two-week siege in the basement of the parliament building in central
Tbilisi.
A rebel spokesman was quoted as saying: 'Gamsakhurdia is a state criminal
and must be sent back to face charges.' However, the Georgian news agency
Yrinda quoted Georgia's acting defence minister, Mr Levan Sharashenidze, as
saying that the two sides had agreed that the fugitive former President
could remain in Armenia for the time being, but that his supporters had to
be disarmed and sent back.
The independent Interfax news agency reported that Mr Gamsakhurdia had asked
Armenia to allow him to fly to the West but gave no specific destination.
Journalists who witnessed the violence in Tbilisi said that after the
demonstrators had passed a hotel, a group of eight to ten armed men - some
wearing masks - appeared and formed a line across the street. They fired
into the air and then some fired at the crowd.
A freelance reporter working for Cable News Network said a group of armed
men cornered him and three other journalists, forcing them to surrender
their videotapes at gunpoint.
Local media put the death toll in two weeks of fighting in the republic at
up to 200 - the worst violence to hit the Soviet Union since the country
broke apart last month. A senior Soviet army officer said two soldiers had
been killed in an attack on their army car in the mountains near Tbilisi
overnight.
Mr Tengiz Sigua, acting prime minister of Georgia, said yesterday the
situation was very bad, and there was a severe shortage of money. Armed
bandits were roaming Tbilisi, and there were several shooting incidents
between bandits and National Guardsmen loyal to the opposition.
Mr Sigua, named by the rebels as a prospective prime minister in a
provisional government, called for unity. 'There should be no vendettas,' he
said in an address to the nation. 'We should unite in the process of
political reconstruction.'
The rebels' military council is due to hand over power to Mr Sigua's
provisional goverment.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 2
