<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JAN 92 / International Company News: Debt downgrade underlines
Chrysler finance struggle
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE SEVERE financial difficulties facing Chrysler, the smallest of the big
three US motor groups, was underscored yesterday when Standard and Poor's,
the credit rating agency, lowered the company's debt rating.
S&amp;P said the reasons included the weakness of the US car market and the fact
that Chrysler had not taken action to improve access to the capital markets
for its important and profitable finance arm, Chrysler Financial.
The leading credit rating agencies reduced Chrysler's debt from investment
grade to 'junk bond' status about a year ago, which made it far more
difficult for the company to raise debt capital on reasonable terms.
Yesterday's move by S&amp;P will reinforce that position.
The agency said it had cut the ratings of both Chrysler and Chrysler
Financial to single-B-plus from double-B-minus. Chrysler said it was
disappointed at the move, which was 'not warranted by the current financial
outlook'.
Chrysler, in common with Detroit rivals General Motors and Ford, is
suffering heavy losses because the US recession has cut demand for cars at a
time when the US industry faces intense competition from Japanese rivals.
S&amp;P said that Chrysler's cash reserves, saleable assets and access to bank
credit should give it adequate financial flexibility at least for 1992.
However, it added that 'negative cash flow this year due to persisting weak
auto markets would leave Chrysler ill-prepared to meet the challenges it
will face thereafter in the intensely competitive North American automobile
industry.'
Chrysler Financial, which plays a central role in supporting the sale of the
company's vehicles and has large non-auto interests, has been shut out of
the traditional credit markets because of the problems of its parent. For
much of the past year Chrysler has been considering ways of raising the
unit's ratings by distancing it from Chrysler.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 24
</PAGE>
