<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JAN 92 / International Company News: Chrysler, General Motors debt
ratings downgraded
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MARTIN DICKSON
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   NEW YORK
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
THE SEVERE financial pressures facing the US automobile industry were
underscored yesterday when one credit agency lowered its rating of General
Motors' debt and another downgraded Chrysler.
However, GM, the biggest of the US car manufacturers, could claim a victory
of sorts in that Moody's Investors Service, the agency which lowered its
senior debt rating, did not downgrade the short-term commercial paper issued
by General Motor Acceptance Corp (GMAC), its finance arm.
GMAC, the largest non-bank financial group in the US, relies on commercial
paper for much of its funding needs. A downgrading by Moody's or Standard &amp;
Poor's, the most influential rating agencies, would have impeded its ability
to tap this market, forcing it to pay higher interest rates.
Moody's cut its rating of GM and GMAC's senior debt from A1 to A2 but
maintained its Prime-1 rating on GMAC's commercial paper.
Fears of a downgrade were a major factor behind GM's announcement last month
of a big restructuring, including the closure of over 20 plants and 70,000
job losses over the next four years.
However, Moody's said its action was based on the fact that 'GM's long-term
competitive position may continue to weaken despite an expected improvement
in the company's cost structure and competitive efficiency'.
Standard &amp; Poor's, which has yet to comment on GM, yesterday cut its ratings
for Chrysler, the smallest of Detroit's Big Three motor manufacturers, and
Chrysler Financial, its finance arm, from double-B-minus to single-B-plus.
S&amp;P said the reasons included the weakness of the US automobile market and
the fact that Chrysler had not taken action to improve access to the capital
markets for its important and profitable finance arm, Chrysler Financial.
Chrysler said it was disappointed at the move, which was 'not warranted by
the current financial outlook'.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
<PAGE>
London Page 24
