<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JAN 92 / International Company News: Air France to buy 40% stake in
Czech airline
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DANIEL GREEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AIR FRANCE is leading a consortium that will pay Dollars 60m for a 40 per
cent stake in Ceskeslovenske Aerolinie (CSA), the Czechoslovakian state
airline, writes Daniel Green. The deal values CSA at Dollars 150m (Pounds
82.4m) and makes Air France the first western airline to become a
shareholder in an existing eastern European carrier.
It would be one of the biggest investments yet for the London-based European
Bank for Reconstruction and Development (EBRD), which is in the consortium.
The EBRD and Caisse des Depots et Consignation, a French financial
institution and a shareholder in Air France, were each contributing Dollars
20m in cash to the consortium, said Air France.
The EBRD said yesterday its board would finalise the level of investment
within eight weeks. The two airlines signed a memorandum of understanding in
Prague on Monday. The deal is subject to approval from the French and
Czechoslovak governments. Air France hopes this will be given by spring.
Air France's investment represents a partial privatisation of CSA. The
remaining 60 per cent will be held by the Czechoslovak state and domestic
financial institutions.
Air France said: 'We were looking for a partner in eastern Europe. Prague is
geographically located right in the centre.' The French state-owned airline
intends to make Prague a secondary European hub after Paris.
'This alliance represents an excellent platform for CSA's future development
as an airline based in the heart of Europe and for Prague as a major hub,'
said Mr Oldrich Churain, CSA director-general.
Of the Dollars 60m being paid for the CSA stake, Air France is paying about
Dollars 6m in cash.
Observer, Page 18
