<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JAN 92 / Labour moves on to offensive with six-point economic plan:
Major says tax increases 'are precisely what this country doesn't need'
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
LABOUR moved on to the political offensive yesterday in the increasingly
frenetic electioneering atmosphere by setting out a six-point short-term
plan to take the UK out of recession.
Mr Neil Kinnock, the Labour leader, accused the prime minister of telling
'whoppers' about Labour's tax plans: he said he detected 'almost a sense of
panic' among the Tories.
Mr Kinnock sounded confident after the last day-long meeting of Labour's
shadow cabinet before the election, which discussed campaigning and endorsed
the programme for long-term economic recovery which will be published today.
He said the Tories' negative campaigning was a sign of their desperation to
provide a distraction from the recession.
Yesterday Mr John Major and Mr Chris Patten, the Tory party chairman,
broadened their attack on the possibility of higher taxes under Labour by
focussing on the economic harm they would do.
The prime minister said substantial tax increases across the board 'would
not only be unwelcome, they would be economically damaging. They are
precisely what this country doesn't need at the moment'. Mr Patten said they
would 'destroy hopes of an economic recovery'.
Mr Major said Labour had spent years condemning the government for
'underfunding' public services and promising to correct this. This
inevitably 'involves expenditure and that expenditure has to be paid for'.
The intense level of campaigning will continue in the coming weeks, whatever
the date chosen for the general election. Mr Major will discuss the
manifesto and campaign tactics in meetings with colleagues at Chequers
towards the end of the week. Recent opinion polls have not shown a clear
lead for either party, and a February election would mean losing the
opportunity to use the Budget to gain popularity, as well as delaying the
introduction of the council tax.
Mr Kinnock rejected Tory assertions that the increase in the top rate would
damage economic recovery, pointing out that in the period of strongest
growth in the mid-1980s the top tax rate was 60 per cent.
With Mr John Smith, the shadow chancellor, he reiterated that Labour's
planned top tax rate would affect only people earning 'well over Pounds
30,000', and that 88 per cent of earners would not be affected by the
removal of the ceiling on national insurance contributions. Labour would not
spend more than the country could afford, they promised.
Labour's six-point programme includes enhanced first-year capital allowances
for new investment in manufacturing; creating a new skills fund and a job
experience programme, estimated to cost Pounds 800m-Pounds 900m; and setting
up a cash-limited enterprise investment scheme.
Mr Paddy Ashdown, the Liberal Democrat leader, joined the fray, saying the
government was not coming clean about how it would fund any tax cuts and
that Labour was not telling the whole truth about its public spending.
Major hits out at pessimism over economy, Page 6
