<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JAN 92 / Stress blamed for failed mergers
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MERGERS and acquisitions frequently fail to live up to financial
expectations because companies place too much importance on finance, and
spend too little time planning for the stressful effects of change on their
staff.
That is the finding of a three-year study of mergers and acquisitions being
unveiled today by occupational psychologists.
More than half of all mergers and acquisitions do not achieve their
financial potential in spite of being presented to shareholders as a
strategy for wealth creation, according to psychologists Dr Sue Cartwright
and Professor Cary Cooper from the University of Manchester Institute of
Science and Technology.
In addition, mergers and acquisitions 'have become associated with lowered
productivity, higher labour turnover and absenteeism, worse strike records
and poorer accident rates'.
While companies examine in detail the financial considerations of taking
over or merging with another organisation, the 'people' issues are very much
of an afterthought, Dr Cartwright and Professor Cooper will tell the British
Psychological Society's annual occupational psychology conference in
Liverpool.
The consequence is that even a genuine merger between highly compatible
companies is often perceived as a takeover by the staff, the researchers
say.
Mergers are found to be more stressful because of the greater degree of
ambiguity and the frequently long periods of uncertainty while negotiations
are in progress.
Middle managers are found to be the most stressed group because they are not
close enough to the top to know exactly what is going on, but still have to
manage the fears of more junior staff.
For example, a detailed study of the mental health of 157 middle managers
after the merger of two building societies found the managers had 'adverse
mental health scores significantly higher than the normal population', and
an 'abnormally high percentage' recorded scores 'comparable with
psycho-neurotic hospital outpatients'.
Because of the secrecy surrounding acquisitions and mergers, companies do
not learn from each other's mistakes. 'Culture audits' need to be conducted
before companies combine so the best aspects of each organisation can be
brought to the new joint venture, the researchers conclude.
Data group mergers, Page 9
Health check, Page 12
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
