<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JAN 92 / Data group merger values rise
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALAN CANE
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE VALUE of mergers and acquisitions among UK information-services
companies rose by 4 per cent last year to Pounds 669m from Pounds 645m in
1990, compared with a peak of Pounds 1.1bn in 1988.
The number of transactions, 102, was down on both 1988 (120) and 1990 (138),
according to the figures compiled by Broadview Associates, a firm of
financial advisers.
Broadview argues that the rise in total value when the economy and the
information-services industry are in difficulties underlines the importance
of mergers and acquisitions as a vehicle for growth in the sector.
The proportion of deals financed through shares rose from 8 per cent in 1990
to 18 per cent, but cash continued to be the main instru-ment.
The four largest transactions accounted for 56 per cent of the total value
of deals: Electronic Data Systems bought SD-Scicon for Pounds 162m; First
Data Resources, an American Express subsidiary, bought Signet for Pounds
100m; a management buy-out at Thorn EMI Software created Data Sciences,
valued at Pounds 82m; ACT Group purchased Quotient for Pounds 27.4m.
</TEXT>
