<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JAN 92 / Institute of British Geographers' Conference in Sheffield:
Japanese claims questioned
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ANDREW JACK
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
JAPANESE INVESTORS in north-east England are not as innovative as has been
assumed, two academics from Newcastle Polytechnic told the conference
yesterday.
Dr Frank Peck and Dr Ian Stone said that, while Japanese companies claimed
to have a very high incidence of modern management techniques, detailed
analysis showed that their actual practices were often markedly less
sophisticated.
Linguistic confusion and a desire to appear at the forefront of modern
production techniques meant that questions to Japanese companies were often
misunderstood or the answers exaggerated, they said.
For example, 69 per cent of all inward investors said that they had
'single-status' plants with no distinction between managers and shopfloor
workers, 49 per cent said they had workers' consultative committees, 39 per
cent 'just-in-time' production and 71 per cent team-working. For Japanese
investors, those figures were 100 per cent, 77 per cent, 62 per cent and 100
per cent respectively.
In each case, detailed interviews revealed that the techniques as generally
understood were often not applied, or they were not implemented in vital
production areas.
The survey covered 84 of the 106 inward investors of the past decade in
north-eastern manufacturing plants with more than 20 employees.
</TEXT>
