FT  08 JAN 92 / Fullemploy training group collapses
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD EVANS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
FULLEMPLOY, Britain's only national training organisation for ethnic
minorities, has gone into liquidation after a long struggle for additional
funds. Buchler Phillips, the financial consultants, have been appointed
liquidators and will hold meetings with creditors in the next fortnight.
The collapse which will embarrass the government, was caused mainly by a
decision by the Home Office last year to withhold its Pounds 250,000 annual
grant following an investigation by the Charity Commissioners into
unsuccessful Fullemploy expansion schemes.
Ethnic-minority unemployment remains higher than in the majority community,
and the charity's efforts to tackle the problem have been supported by many
leading organisations in the private and public sectors.
Mr David Buchler, a partner in Buchler Phillips, said last night that
Fullemploy would continue in business to allow time for talks with potential
purchasers. Grand Metropolitan Community Services Trust has offered to
indemnify him against trading losses during the next few weeks.
A total of Pounds 446,000 has been raised recently from the private sector
through cash, loans written off and new guarantees.
This came from a group of leading companies and organisations including the
Bank of England, BP, International Business Machines, Prudential, Marks and
Spencer, Commercial Union, Boots, Lloyds Bank, WH Smith and Rosehaugh. These
funds will now be returned.
</TEXT>
