<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JAN 92 / UK News (Employment): End to 'military' management urged
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DIANE SUMMERS, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
OLD-STYLE military manage-ment needs to be replaced by a more 'feminine'
approach, Dr Beverly Alimo-Metcalfe, a senior psychology lecturer at Leeds
University, claimed at a British Psychological Society conference yesterday.
She said at the society's occupational psychology conference in Liverpool
that 'feminine' styles, which companies will need to adopt in order to
survive, remain discriminated against by job-selection procedures.
She added that many companies accepted that they would have to abandon
'military' organisation. 'Heroic', invariably male, company leadership would
need to be replaced by female management styles, she explained. There was,
however, evidence that selection procedures still reflected old values. For
example, women were discriminated against in group discussions which formed
part of interviews, as men dominated conversations.
Research by two other psychologists presented at the conference suggested
that women were not prepared to adopt what were seen as male patterns of
behaviour in order to win promotion.
According to Dr Catherine Cassell from Sheffield Polytechnic and Dr Susan
Walsh from Sheffield University, women were often forced into 'managing
their femaleness' to survive at work.
That meant they had to 'mother' and 'nurture' male colleagues, massage egos,
or use their sexuality by flirting with or by flattering the men around
them.
</TEXT>
