<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JAN 92 / UK News (Employment): Colleges fail to claim tax relief for
training
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LISA WOOD, Labour Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THOUSANDS of financially troubled colleges of further education and private
providers of training are failing to register for tax relief worth more than
Pounds 20m in 1992-93.
Tax relief was announced in the last Budget on courses leading to National
Vocational Qualifications (NVQs) up to level 4 - the vocational equivalent
of a degree.
Individual trainees, according to new guidelines, would pay reduced fees
from which basic-rate tax has been deducted. But providers of training can
claim tax relief only if they register with the Inland Revenue before April
6.
The Department of Employment said yesterday that only 430 of the 7,000
providers of training who were eligible for relief had claimed it. They
included colleges of further education and private providers of training.
An estimated 250,000 people pay to study for NVQs. The government's
objective in announcing the tax relief was to encourage more people to
invest in their own training and self-development.
It estimated the cost of the tax relief at Pounds 20m in 1992-93, rising to
Pounds 40m in the mid-1990s when all NVQs are avail-able.
The Inland Revenue said it was arranging a series of seminars to explain to
trainers how the tax relief would work. These will run during February and
March.
</TEXT>
