<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JAN 92 / UK News (Employment): AEU signals move towards white-collar
recruitment
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID GOODHART, Labour Editor
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A RECRUITMENT battle for white-collar staff and technicians in the
engineering industry could erupt if the merger between the AEU engineering
union and the EETPU electricians' union goes ahead later this year.
Mr Gavin Laird, AEU general secretary, said yesterday that the EETPU had a
'viable, successful white-collar section'. The AEU has not traditionally
recruited in the white-collar area which is dominated by the MSF general
technical union.
The merger is likely to form the basis of an AEU attempt to win recognition
rights in the white-collar area from the Engineering Employers' Federation.
The merger proposals are going to a ballot of the members of both unions
between February 17 and March 2. The result is expected on March 4.
Mr Laird also said yesterday that single-union deals between employers and
either the AEU or the EETPU will not be nullified by the merger.
'The single-union deals will remain exactly as they are, but if they need to
be renegotiated it will be with the merged union,' said Mr Laird.
Initially the two unions will remain quasi-autonomous sections, with their
own rule books. The biggest obstacle to a fuller merger is the fact that the
AEU elects officials while the EETPU appoints them. In the longer term, the
EETPU rules are likely to prevail. AEU elections for officials have recently
attracted turn outs of less than 20 per cent.
The AEU yesterday published the results of a poll of members' attitudes to
the merger. Of 3,000 members polled at random, 24 per cent responded. Those
who said they would vote for a merger made up 49 per cent, with only 12 per
cent saying they would vote against and 39 per cent undecided.
Nearly 60 per cent of respondents said they expected to be worse off this
year compared with last year.
</TEXT>
