<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JAN 92 / Carmakers hope for a late visit from Santa: How falls in
profits and a collapse in sales made last year one the industry would rather
forget
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JOHN GRIFFITHS
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
HUMILIATING falls into loss and a collapse of new car sales turned last year
into one the motor industry would much rather forget.
Total new car sales plunged 20.74 per cent to 1,592,326, the lowest level
for nine years, and nearly one third down on the record 2.3m recorded only
two years previously.
Manufacturers' profits tumbled - Ford and Rover in particular suffered
substantial losses. Ford has already warned that the losses will be 'far
worse' than its 1990 pre-tax deficit of Pounds 274m.
For dealers and distributors, there was a rapidly increasing list of
receiverships and bankruptcies as a vicious re-run of the discounting wars
in the early 1980s took its toll. According to the Retail Motor Industry
Federation, by the middle of this year more than 800 franchised dealers -
more than 10 per cent of the total - will have been forced out of business
in 24 months.
There was a grim rash of job losses in all areas of the industry. The
Society of Motor Manufacturers and Traders, whose statistics yesterday
described the miseries of last year's market in fine detail, predicts that
40,000 jobs will have gone in the year to mid-1992, adding to 25,000 already
lost since mid-1990.
The misery is not over yet. In the UK, few industry chiefs see many signs of
the revival in business confidence they say is essential to kickstart the
industry back to life.
A consensus figure for sales this year is about 1.75m, assuming - as many in
the industry do - that Mr Norman Lamont, the chancellor, will not belatedly
adopt the guise of Santa Claus in his Budget and abolish special car tax and
give other reliefs the industry has long sent pleading letters for to the
Treasury grotto.
Some production lines in the UK were kept busy by Germany and some other
continental markets, with output falling only 3.9 per cent to 1.58m in the
first 11 months of the year. Those lines are now also coming off the boil.
Worsening the uncertainty is the imminent arrival of a report by the
Monopolies and Mergers Commission on allegedly high car prices in the UK,
and whether the existing system of exclusively franchised dealers works
against consumers' interests. A 'thumbs down' from the commission would add
substantially to the woes in the industry.
Yet some crumbs of comfort could be found among yesterday's statistics for
at least some of the industry.
The December market was down, but the fall of 7.26 per cent was less severe
than in previous months. In all, 58,274 cars were registered in December,
although not necessarily sold. Manufacturers will register cars without
having sold them to real buyers if their market share looks particularly
bad.
In the second half of the year, sales were more than 16 per cent below the
corresponding period a year before, compared with nearly 29 per cent in the
second quarter.
Imports were held back, although only marginally. The importers' market
share fell to 55.67 per cent for the year as a whole, compared with 56.74
per cent in 1990. It was only a token but, for the first time in years, the
UK share of the market tipped over 50 per cent  - knocking imports down to
49.69 per cent - in December.
Last night the SMMT was nursing a faint hope that the industry's balance of
trade performance might have earned it some brownie points in Whitehall.
After nearly a decade of increasing deficits, reaching Pounds 6.5bn in 1989,
the deficit fell to Pounds 1.5bn last year.
While much of the reduction is simply the result of the fall in the UK
market, Sir Hal Miller, SMMT chief executive and departing Tory MP for
Bromsgrove, was nevertheless able to point out yesterday that 'we are still
the country's leading exporter'.
Fortunes varies for individual manufacturers. Ford, the UK market leader for
well over a decade, continued to suffer. Its market share last year fell to
24.24 per cent, down more than one percentage point on 1990 and a far cry
from the 30 per cent share it took for granted in the late 1980s.
Mr Ian McAllister, who took over as Ford of Britain's chairman on January 1,
insists that this year the rot will be reversed. Part of the reason for the
fall, he says, has been the absence of performance models such as the XR3i
version of the Escort, which has been delayed by the late arrival of new
engines. Such cars have accounted in the past for one percentage point of
Ford's market share and will do so again, he says. He also promises a new
model launch every six months over the next 2 1/2 years.
Vauxhall, in spite of expecting to remain profitable this year, could also
be counted among the year's losers in that its market share fell slightly
last year after several years of gains.
In sales terms at least, among the UK-based manufacturers both Peugeot
Talbot and Rover could count themselves as winners, with Peugeot in
particular winning an increased share of the market. Its prospects should be
further enhanced next year when a second model joins production of the
Peugeot 405 at its Ryton plant near Coventry.
Nissan, operating its own distribution system in the UK from January 1 after
its split with Mr Octav Botnar's Nissan UK, suffered badly from the fall-out
from the row. Its market share fell to just over 4 per cent - only half of
its share in the late 1980s.
Among the volume importers, the Fiat group's suffering continued, with the
combined share of Fiat, Alfa Romeo and Lancia sinking to just under 2.5 per
cent. Were it not for Alfa's 164 flagship, still selling well and helping
Alfa to increase its own share last year, the group's figures would look
worse. Fiat is committing Pounds 100m to its UK operations in an effort to
reverse the decline.
As expected, the UK's specialist and luxury carmakers were shown to have
suffered most. Rolls-Royce and Jaguar sales were virtually halved. And
proving that the disease is not confined to UK luxury carmakers, Porsche's
sales were down by 42 per cent to 1,612.
The year's winners among importers and specialist producers, measured by an
increase in market share rather than unit sales, included BMW, which reaped
the benefit of its new 3-series model, and Lotus, which missed increasing
unit sales by a mere eight cars.
The feature of yesterday's statistics which must give the European industry
most pause for thought relates to Far Eastern producers. Every Japanese
manufacturer, with the exception of Nissan, increased its market share.
Apart from a handful of new imports from South Africa, every company which
increased both market share and unit sales was from Japan, Korea or
Malaysia. The winners were Daihatsu, Hyundai, Isuzu, Kia, Suzuki and Proton.
No European producer figured in that category.
