<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JAN 92 / Yarrow chairman warns on future of warship builders
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID WHITE, Defence Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
AT LEAST one of the UK's four warship builders will be forced out of
business, Sir Robert Easton, chairman of Yarrow Shipbuilders, the Clydeside
yard, predicted yesterday.
Yarrow, part of the GEC group, is competing against the Tyneside yard Swan
Hunter, Cumbria-based VSEL and the Southampton yard Vosper Thornycroft to
build a batch of up to three Type 23 anti-submarine frigates for the Royal
Navy.
Lobbying for the order has intensified, with a decision expected next month
or in March ahead of the general election. Of the 10 Type 23 orders placed
so far, six have been won by Yarrow and the rest by Swan Hunter.
Orders in prospect would not be sufficient to sustain all four yards, Sir
Robert said in London.
'I believe that there are too many shipyards and that they won't all
survive,' he said. 'There are clear indications that three yards might
survive at a certain level, but two yards would be able to pick up what is
available in the UK.'
No other company would challenge VSEL's position as sole UK builder of
nuclear-powered submarines, Sir Robert said, because of the high
infrastructure costs involved and the lack of export opportunities. But the
same did not apply to Vosper Thornycroft's niche in mine warfare vessels
made of glass-reinforced plastic (GRP).
Royal Navy plans for more GRP minehunters were shelved last year. But
Yarrow, which has an idle GRP facility, would compete 'very severely' for
the contract when it was revived, Sir Robert said.
He said that Yarrow alone would be capable of fulfilling the UK's entire
surface-ship programme, but did not expect the government to favour a
monopoly.
To spread the forthcoming Type 23 frigate order between different yards
would be 'a nonsense', Sir Robert said. Yards needed sufficient production
volume to achieve economies of scale.
Yarrow is expected to conclude a Malaysian order for two corvettes worth
about Pounds 150m within the next three months, filling an export vacuum.
Mr Tom King, the defence secretary, was 'perhaps rather premature' in
announcing an imminent deal in September, Sir Robert said. However, problems
over the choice of combat system for the vessels had now been 'more or less
resolved'.
</TEXT>
