<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JAN 92 / Scots may elect for a German influence: A growing Labour
interest in the proportional-representation option
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By DAVID OWEN
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
PROPORTIONAL representation based on the German model is emerging as
favourite to be chosen by Labour as the basis for electing candidates to its
proposed Scottish parliament.
Such a move would not be binding on the party nationally, but would have a
strong influence on its debate on electoral reform. It would also set a
precedent for abandoning the UK's first-past-the-post electoral system.
Mr Alistair Darling, Labour's constitutional spokesman, said a consensus was
developing among Scottish members in favour of an 'additional member' system
to elect assembly members.
Under this format, voters cast two votes - one for an individual
constituency candidate, as at present, and another for a party.
Labour is committed to establishing a directly elected Scottish assembly
with significant legislative and tax-raising powers 'at the earliest
possible moment'.
The preferred approach would be similar to the system that has been used in
Germany since 1948, although Mr Darling stresses that the intention is not
to import it 'in pure form'.
Labour would want to adapt it in order to meet Scotland's circumstances, he
said.
In Germany, half the parliamentary seats are filled with the
first-past-the-post winners, while the other half are allocated from party
lists, reflecting voters' party preferences.
Mr Darling said that Labour would not necessarily stick to this 50:50 ratio.
The party is veering towards the additional-member approach - and away from
the alternative-vote model which has also been considered - as it would
maintain a constituency link, Mr Darling said.
Mr Darling said Labour has 'no plans' to address what it regards as the
separate issue of Scottish representation at Westminster if the proposed
assembly is created.
As Scotland is already among the parts of the UK which are numerically
over-represented in the Commons, this appears to leave its plans vulnerable
to attack on the grounds that they would pamper an area accounting for an
important slice of the party's Westminster representation.
Labour has promised that it would grant the assembly power to adjust
expenditure levels by varying Scottish income-tax rates.
The body's other responsibilities would include the electricity industry,
the Scottish Development Agency, industrial training and the operation of
regional development policies.
The party's commission on electoral systems is due to present its
recommendations to the national executive committee at the end of this
month.
LABOUR'S CHANCES of election victory will be damaged by a fall in electoral
registration in marginal seats, according to a survey of last year's
registers by the independent Electoral Reform Society. 'The short-term
effect will be to steepen the electoral mountain facing Labour at the next
general election,' it said.
The sharpest declines were in London, with falls of more than 4,500 since
1987 in each of five constituencies. Many people are believed not to have
registered in order to avoid the community charge.
The biggest fall, at nearly 10,000, was in Putney where Mr David Mellor,
chief secretary to the Treasury, holds the seat with a majority of 6,436.
Sharp drops were also recorded in four other Tory-held London seats: Hornsey
and Wood Green (majority 1,779), Kensington (4,447), Hampstead and Highgate
(2,221) and Streatham (2,407).
The society predicted that this year's electoral register - to be released
on February 15 - would reveal a further fall.
Electoral Statistics, HMSO, Pounds 6.20.
</TEXT>
