<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JAN 92 / Major hits out at pessimism over economy
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By ALISON SMITH
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
RECENT PESSIMISM about the economy has been 'overdone', Mr John Major, the
prime minister, said last night.
'If you listen to some of the dismal Johnnies you might never realise what
has been achieved in the last year,' he told an audience of businessmen in
Newcastle upon Tyne.
There were many encouraging developments in the economy. He pointed to the
fall in inflation, the reduction in the interest rate differential against
the D-Mark, and the slowdown in the trend rate of increase in unemployment.
Mr Major also highlighted the fact that people with annually adjusted
mortgages would only now be seeing the benefit of the cuts in interest rates
over the past year.
Expressing confidence about the UK's prospects for the 1990s, he warned that
this depended on people ignoring 'siren voices offering quack remedies' of
higher taxation and re-regulation. There was no 'magic moment, no precise
point when recession lies clearly in the past, while recovery stretches out
into a better future'.
Mr Major said economic data would show irregular patterns while the
recession was ending and the recovery beginning. He emphasised that
government could not and should not try to fine-tune the economy in response
to the latest economic statistics.
He acknowledged that the UK economy had not performed as well as had been
hoped in the last year, and attributed this to difficulties in the world
economy.
Rejecting the accusation that the government had no industrial strategy, Mr
Major said that its policies of privatisation, cutting taxes, freeing up the
labour market and above all combating inflation, were based on creating the
right framework for business. 'Our job is to provide a stable and
predictable economic framework, with responsible monetary and budgetary
policies, so that business and individuals can have the confidence to take
the right decisions.'
He contrasted this with Labour's policies of setting up a national
investment bank, introducing a minimum wage and bringing in a payroll tax to
finance a statutory training programme.
Mr Major countered Labour's charge that the government's refusal to sign up
to the social chapter at the EC summit in Maastricht was because they did
not want British workers to benefit from higher working standards.
The government had taken the stance because it believed such matters should
be settled between management and employees.
</TEXT>
