<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JAN 92 / Chrysler chief accuses Japan of stifling car imports
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Foreign Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
MR Lee Iacocca, chairman of Chrysler, yesterday accused the Japanese of
being 'out of step with the rest of the world'.
Mr Iacocca, General Motors chairman Mr Robert Stempel, and Ford chairman Mr
Harold Poling are accompanying President Bush on his visit to Japan. Today
the chiefs of the big three US carmakers join talks with Japanese government
and business leaders on moves to reduce Tokyo's huge trade surplus.
The Chrysler chairman said that since 1985 Chrysler had sold 100,000 cars in
Europe but only 1,000 in Japan. 'There is something wrong with the system.
We're here to try to change some basic (Japanese) policies that would make
it easier for American cars to go into Japanese dealer showrooms.'
He blamed the Japanese for contributing to last year's Dollars 41bn (Pounds
22.5bn) US trade deficit with Japan, 75 per cent of which was in cars and
car parts.
Meanwhile, Ford, the second largest US car maker, announced that it is to
export Ford-badged right-hand drive vehicles to Japan and the UK, the
world's biggest right-hand-drive car markets, for the first time since the
early 1900s.
It said yesterday that a right-hand-drive version of the new generation Ford
Probe, a sporty coupe due for launch in the US in mid-1992, would be built
in the US for export from autumn 1993.
Ironically, the Ford Probe is built at the Michigan assembly plant of Mazda,
Ford's Japanese affiliate in which it holds a 25 per cent stake.
The Probe is a Ford-derived version of the Mazda MX-6 coupe.
Mr Allan Gilmour, president of Ford's automotive operations, said that the
right-hand-drive version of the Probe would be 'merely the beginning of a
series of vehicles built in America that will be exportable to
right-hand-drive markets.'
Historically Ford and other US car makers have chosen to manufacture
vehicles locally around the world, but Mr Gilmour said that the convergence
of product concepts and technologies meant that Ford was planning to produce
in the US a 'greater variety of right-hand-drive products for Japan and the
UK.'
The introduction of the Ford Probe to the UK will be welcomed by Ford's
hard-pressed British dealers, which are suffering in part from the lack of a
sporty coupe in their range to rival the successful Vauxhall Calibra. Ford
has lacked a coupe in Europe since it stopped production of the Ford Capri
in 1987.
Japanese car producers last year increased further their share of US car
sales, adding to mounting US-Japanese trade frictions. Their advance came as
US new car sales fell by 12 per cent to 8.2m, the fourth decline in five
years and the lowest level since 1982.
With the recession in the US car market deepening the big three US car
makers - General Motors, Ford and Chrysler - all suffered heavy losses.
Japanese-badged cars captured 31 per cent of the US new car market last
year, against 28 per cent a year earlier. For the first time Chrysler, the
smallest of the big three, was overtaken by Honda and Toyota.
UK car sales, Page 8.
</TEXT>
