<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JAN 92 / UK officials try to persuade Russians that beef is safe
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By Our Foreign Staff
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
BRITISH and Russian officials in Moscow yesterday sought to settle an
embarrassing row over Russia's reluctance to accept UK beef aid because of
claims that it could bring 'mad cow' disease to Russia.
Veterinary surgeons from the UK and the European Commission were also
meeting their Russian counterparts in an attempt to persuade them that the
beef is safe.
Mrs Lynda Chalker, the minister for overseas development, is scheduled to
fly to St Petersburg tomorrow, when she will seek to defuse the row.
Her visit, to discuss the distribution of Pounds 20m of animal feed grain
sent by the government, was planned before the beef dispute broke out.
The announcement of her visit came as an exasperated British government said
delivery of 2,000 tonnes of frozen beef had been suspended while steps were
taken to persuade the Russian authorities that the beef was free of the 'mad
cow' disease, bovine spongiform encephalopathy.
The beef rejected by Moscow officials at the weekend was the first tranche
of the EC's food aid programme for Russia. It was finally accepted by the
northern Russian city of Murmansk, which has different regulations from
those of Moscow and where no cattle are reared.
The rest of Britain's meat aid consignment - accumulated by the UK under the
EC's Common Agricultural Policy - has been put back into cold storage
pending the return from Moscow later this week of Mr Keith Meldrum, the UK's
chief veterinary officer.
Mr Meldrum, who flew to Moscow on Monday, will hold further talks with the
Russian authorities today.
The Ministry of Agriculture in London confirmed that the beef had come from
UK herds which might have been infected by BSE. But under EC regulations,
the infected parts - mainly bones and offal - could be removed and the meat
safely consumed.
The meat could not be certified in the normal way, however. Only meat from
herds which had been free of the disease for two years could be certified as
BSE-free.
Sir Rodric Braithwaite, the British ambassador in Moscow, said Russian vets
had sought assurances that none of the beef came from farms which had
suffered outbreaks of the disease, but this was impossible to do. The
Russian government was anxious to settle the row quickly, he said. 'They do
want (the aid) and they need it.'
BSE is a brain disorder which has devastated British herds for the past five
years, and has soured trade relations.
</TEXT>
<PUB>The Financial Times
</PUB>
