<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JAN 92 / Moscow applies for full membership of the IMF
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By LIONEL BARBER
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   WASHINGTON
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
RUSSIA yesterday applied for full membership of the International Monetary
Fund and World Bank, the first step towards winning financial support for
its transition from a centralised to a free-market economy, writes Lionel
Barber in Washington.
The request follows President Boris Yeltsin's scrapping of price controls in
the former Soviet republic last week.
The US and other western allies have said they will support Fund and Bank
membership for Russia and other reformist Soviet republics, allowing them
access to development loans once they adopt an IMF reform programme.
Until recently, western countries had vigorously opposed full IMF membership
on the grounds that the Soviet leadership was not prepared to embrace
serious economic reform. The Bush administration now recognises that the IMF
is best placed to assume the burden of direct financial aid and offering
expert advice.
Russia's application came amid US preparations for an international
conference in Washington this month to co-ordinate food and medical aid for
the former Soviet republics.
Up to 60 countries could attend the conference on January 22 and 23, the
State Department said. The meeting will be held at foreign ministers level
and will involve international financial institutions, including the IMF,
World Bank and European Bank for Reconstruction and Development.
Ms Margaret Tutwiler, State Department chief spokeswoman, said the aim was
to organise a division of labour to meet 'drastically increasing
humanitarian needs'.
Russia is likely to have to wait at least six months for its request to be
processed, along with an earlier one from Ukraine and Azerbaijan's
yesterday. One reason is the lack of adequate economic data.
The United Nations Security Council looks set to meet on January 30 to
discuss the break-up of the Soviet Union and the role of the UN in the
post-Cold War era. The meeting is partly intended to allay western concerns
about command and control of nuclear weapons and proliferation risks. A
broader aim, however, is to reinforce the authority of Mr Boutros Ghali, the
new secretary-general.
</TEXT>
