<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JAN 92 / Yugoslav army downs EC aircraft: Air force commander
suspended - Defence Ministry plans urgent inquiry
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By JUDY DEMPSEY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
YUGOSLAVIA last night suspended the commander of its air force after the
federal army admitted shooting down a European Community helicopter, killing
five peace monitors.
The European Commission roundly condemned the incident, in which four
Italian soldiers and a French officer died, and called for a full inquiry.
However, EC officials said international efforts to end the fighting would
be stepped up.
In a short, but unusually frank, statement issued through Tanjug, the
Belgrade-based news agency, the Defence Ministry said one of its aircraft
had shot down one EC monitoring helicopter and damaged a second.
The federal secretariat of national defence expressed 'deep regret' over 'an
unwanted and tragic event'. It promised an urgent inquiry and said it would
take legal measures against those responsible.
Western diplomats said that the move by the Serb-dominated rump Yugoslav
presidency to suspend Colonel Zvonko Jurjevic, the air force commander,
might be an attempt to bring the armed forces under political control.
Diplomats were surprised by the Defence Ministry admission. One said: 'The
fact that the army admitted to it . . . quickly, and promised a full
inquiry, makes me cautiously optimistic that the peace process can
continue.'
Previous army statements have tended to be sharply critical of independence
moves by the republics of Slovenia and Croatia, which are expecting
recognition by most EC countries on January 15.
The incident happened early yesterday as EC officials and monitors were
being flown from Belgrade, the Serbian and federal capital, via Hungary, to
Zagreb, the Croatian capital.
The five dead, the first casualties among EC monitors in the Yugoslav civil
war, included the Italian pilot and co-pilot of the helicopter, which
exploded in mid-air. The second helicopter, carrying four Italians and a
Belgian, crashlanded safely.
The EC said it was 'appalled and dismayed' by the incident but Britain and
Portugal, current EC president, said it would not be allowed to damage the
chances of peace.
Mr Douglas Hurd, UK foreign secretary, said: 'The tragedy is bound to
influence people's attitudes, but I think it will have the effect of
redoubling efforts to achieve peace rather than weakening them.'
Lord Carrington, chairman of the EC-sponsored peace talks which are due to
resume in Brussels tomorrow, described it as a 'tragic incident' and hoped
it would not scupper peace hopes.
The UN Security Council continued with its peace plans. It is asking 21
countries to provide two to three military observers.
