<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JAN 92 / InterCity links threatened by sell-off, BR report says
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS and JAMES BUXTON
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
DOZENS OF towns and cities in the UK will lose their InterCity rail links
under the government's plans for the privatisation of British Rail,
according to a confidential BR document.
They include every InterCity destination in Scotland north of Glasgow and
Edinburgh; every InterCity destination in Wales except Newport and Cardiff;
and a score of English towns and cities such as Blackpool, Bradford, Hull,
Lincoln, Worcester, Hereford and Penzance.
The document, seen by Mr Brian Wilson, Labour's Scottish transport
spokesman, threatens to provoke strong opposition to the privatisation plans
from MPs representing the constituencies affected - many of them
Conservative.
But Mr Malcolm Rifkind, the transport secretary, yesterday dismissed it as
'scaremongering'.
Although the document is likely to be seen as an attempt by BR employees to
undermine the privatisation plans, it presents a plausible analysis of the
likely consequences of selling InterCity to the private sector.
It says that the government's insistence that InterCity should deliver a
rate of return on its assets of 2.5 per cent a year has led to a steady
erosion of services since 1982. A private sector owner, however, would
require a far higher rate of return than this, the document says, leading to
sharp cuts in peripheral services.
It concludes that the lightly used sections of the InterCity network would
be ruthlessly pruned, leaving them as branch lines with connecting services
into the mainline network. Victims would almost certainly include the
Aberdeen and Inverness lines in Scotland, points west of Cardiff in south
Wales, and the Crewe-Holyhead line in north Wales.
In England, it would mean the probable loss of InterCity links for points
west of Plymouth in the south-west, for Worcester and Hereford in the West
Midlands, and for branches off the main InterCity network to places such as
Blackpool in the north-west and Hull, Lincoln and Grimsby in the north-east.
The paper also questions whether a private sector owner would have the
resources to fund BR's planned Pounds 750m upgrading of the west coast main
line from London Euston to the West Midlands, the north and Scotland.
Mr Rifkind is expected to produce his white paper on the privatisation of BR
later this month, although the date may slip into February.
Yesterday he said in an interview on BBC Radio Scotland: 'British Rail is a
monopoly and some of its staff, possibly including the person who wrote this
report, would like to keep it as a monopoly and not allow anybody else to
run rail services. That's not my approach.'
</TEXT>
