   SAO PAULO
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
VASP, the Brazilian airline, is cutting its workforce by 5.5 per cent in the
face of a nation-wide recession which threw the company into losses of up to
Dollars 60m for 1991.
Although Vasp won some market share from domestic competitors last year its
ticket sales fell by 8 per cent as the recession in the Brazilian airline
industry began to bite. Some 560 employees will be laid off out of a
workforce of 11,000.
Mr Wagner Canhedo, the president and leading shareholder, launched an
aggressive expansion campaign for the airline after the group's
privatisation in 1990. The company expanded into the international market
and has routes to the west coast of the US, Argentina and Aruba.
Mr Carlos Brighi, a company spokesman, said the Vasp's troubles would not
alter its plans. He said it intended to invest about Dollars 2.5bn in the
future and hoped to win routes to Miami, Brussels and Seoul.
