<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JAN 92 / Reluctant spenders hindering recovery
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By EMMA TUCKER, Economics Staff
</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>
   A FALL in personal disposable income
</DATELINE>
<TEXT>
and continued reluctance by consumers to spend rather than save - hindered
the recovery of consumer demand in the second half of last year, Central
Statistical Office figures showed yesterday.
Real personal disposable income fell by 0.2 per cent in the third quarter
compared with the second and by 0.6 per cent compared with the third quarter
of 1990.
The savings ratio, which measures personal savings as a percentage of total
personal disposable income, dropped only marginally - from 11.2 per cent in
the second quarter to 10.9 per cent in the third.
The state of company finances provided no sign of relief for the economy,
with seasonally adjusted figures from the CSO revealing a financial deficit
of Pounds 2.5bn in the third quarter compared with Pounds 1.4bn in the
second.
Mr Kevin Gardiner, an economist at Warburg Securities, said that, in spite
of the latest increase, the corporate sector's financial deficit would
probably continue to shrink - the trend in previous quarters - as companies
ran down stocks rather than invested.
The increase could be explained partly by a jump of 24 per cent in
third-quarter dividend payments to Pounds 5.8bn from Pounds 4.7bn in the
second quarter. At the same time, the rate of destocking eased from a Pounds
1.7bn reduction in the second quarter to Pounds 0.7bn in the third.
Gross trading profits of the UK corporate sector, net of stock appreciation,
stayed at about Pounds 17.9bn, similar to the second quarter.
However, the figure was maintained by North Sea oil companies' gross trading
profits. Those increased by 22 per cent to Pounds 1.5bn in the third quarter
from Pounds 1.2bn in the second, thanks mainly to increased crude oil sales.
Non-North Sea oil companies' gross trading profits fell between the second
and third quarters from Pounds 16.7bn to Pounds 16.3bn.
Mr Michael Saunders, UK economist for Salomon Brothers International in
London, said the higher savings trend in the personal and company sectors
would continue to hinder the recovery of the economy.
'Consumer spending is going to stay sluggish for the rest of the year, and
in turn that means that the recovery of the overall economy is going to be
very weak,' he said.
The higher company deficits, acting as an encouragement to cut investment,
were also likely to hinder growth.
'The financial position of the corporate sector is sufficiently weak that
the emphasis is still going to be on saving and hence on retrenching rather
than investing,' said Mr Saunders.
The latest squeeze on employment was highlighted by the modest increase in
wages and salaries before tax from Pounds 71.8bn in the second quarter to
Pounds 72.5bn in the third. Income-tax payments were up only 1.6 per cent
compared with the third quarter of 1990. Benefits and transfer payments from
the government were up 15.6 per cent.
Mr Gardiner said the figures showed that the personal and corporate sectors
were still adjusting to the financial excesses of the late 1980s.
The Treasury said, however, that it was confident the savings ratio would
decline this year.
There was scope for some fall in the savings ratio in the coming year as
consumer demand began to recover in response to lower interest rates and
inflation, and as personal wealth increased, said the Treasury.
</TEXT>
