<HEADLINE>
FT  08 JAN 92 / MPs seek reversal of port sale decision
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RICHARD TOMKINS, Transport Correspondent
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A CROSS-PARTY delegation of MPs is to seek a meeting with Mr John Major, the
prime minister, in a final attempt to overturn the bitterly resented outcome
of the Tees &amp; Hartlepool port privatisation.
But transport ministers were yesterday standing their ground, indicating
that there would be no about-turn unless significant new information emerged
before next week's ratification of the decision.
The MPs are urging the prime minister to reverse the decision to sell the
trust port to Humberside Holdings, a private consortium, instead of the
hotly tipped management-employee buy-out team headed by Mr John Hackney, the
port's chief executive. The decision has caused uproar in the ports industry
because other trusts fear their own management-employee buy-out bids will
also be defeated.
Mr Stuart Bell, Labour MP for Middlesbrough, has sent a 13-page submission
to Mr Major detailing allegations that the Tees &amp; Hartlepool Port Authority
conducted the sale of the port improperly in at least seven respects.
Mr Bell's submission says two of the directors of Humberside Holdings had
been directors of two dock service companies that went into liquidation
during the abolition of the dock labour scheme in 1989, leaving the taxpayer
to pay their liabilities of Pounds 6.6m in redundancy payments.
He claims the authority did not take this into account when considering
whether Humberside Holdings met a key criterion of the sale: the bidders'
previous record of meeting their commitments.
Another allegation is that Humberside Holdings was given the opportunity to
introduce additional investors and increase its bid from Pounds 100m to
Pounds 180m during the competition, while the buy-out team was given no such
chance to raise its Pounds 150m bid.
The last opportunity to overturn the decision will be on Tuesday evening,
when MPs are asked to approve a parliamentary order setting out the
provisions for clawing back any property profits made by the port's new
owners.
But the government will use its majority to force the measure through and Mr
Malcolm Rifkind, the transport secretary, is expected to confirm the sale
the next day.
</TEXT>
