<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JAN 92 / International Company News: Revco hearing set to start
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By NIKKI TAIT
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A BANKRUPTCY court hearing to consider the stalemate situation at Revco, the
Ohio-based drugstore chain, is to begin tomorrow.
Over the weekend, none of the three rival reorganisation plans put forward
for the bankrupt retailer won outright backing from creditors. The
Revco-backed creditor plan had majority support from four of the seven
groups of creditors - the bank and trade creditor classes, and two classes
of bondholders.
A proposal from Rite-Aid, which essentially involved the competing drug
retailer in acquiring Revco, won support from two classes of creditors. A
third plan from Jack Eckerd, another drugstore chain, had support from one
class.
Revco appeared hopeful that the weight of support in favour of the creditor
plan would encourage the bankruptcy court judge to force this plan on other
dissenting groups. However, there was no sign that Rite-Aid would back out
of the contest and Revco conceded that it expected some objections to be
voiced at the court hearing.
Revco was taken private via a Dollars 1.25bn leveraged buy-out in 1986, but
filed for protection from its creditors under Chapter 11 of the US
bankruptcy code in mid-1988.
It runs around 1,140 drug stores.
</TEXT>
