<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JAN 92 / UK Company News: Europe tops company shopping lists
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By MICHIYO NAKAMOTO
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
THE US ceded its position as the most favoured market for acquisitions by UK
companies to continental Europe last year, according to a survey of UK
companies' acquisitions and divestments in the US conducted by JP Mervis,
the corporate finance advisers, writes Michiyo Nakamoto.
UK companies spent Dollars 2.9bn (Pounds 1.59bn) to buy 113 companies in the
US in 1991, compared with a total of Dollars 3.5bn spent on 150 acquisitions
in Europe. Almost as much - Dollars 2.7bn - was realised from US sales.
The value of British acquisitions in the US last year was 74 per cent down
on the near-Dollars 11bn spent in 1990 and 91 per cent lower than the 1988
peak of Dollars 33.5bn spent on 425 US companies.
Most sectors experienced a waning of interest. A notable exception was the
medical industry where the value of acquisitions increased from Dollars 25m
to Dollars 238m and the number of companies bought remained at five.
The food, beverages and agriculture sector was another exception, with the
value of acquisitions more than doubled to Dollars 233.2m (Dollars 101.5m)
despite a drop in the number of companies acquired from seven in 1990 to
three.
The natural resources exploration and services sector fell from the top
position in 1990 with Dollars 2.52bn to Dollars 99m. The consumer products
and services sector came top this year with Dollars 638m of acquisitions.
