<HEADLINE>
FT  07 JAN 92 / TV channel to cover all Commons debates
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
   By RAYMOND SNODDY
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
A TELEVISION channel offering full coverage of the Commons will be launched
on Monday when MPs return after the Christmas recess.
The Parliamentary Channel is the creation of nine cable television companies
and will be available to more than 200,000 homes with cable throughout the
UK.
The channel, which will be run as a non-profit venture, is similar to C-Span
in the US which has provided coverage of Congress for the past 10 years and
is available in about 52m homes.
Ms Miranda Curtis, general manager of The Parliamentary Channel, said: 'The
idea is to provide unadorned coverage of the proceedings as they happen. We
will not provide analysis or commentary because other people can do that
very much better than we can.'
The channel will simply distribute the 'raw' feed provided by Commons
Committee Television, an independent television producer, as long as the
Commons sits.
The channel will be run for the nine consortium members by United Artists
Programming. The nine include leading cable television operators such as
Comcast, Videotron and CUC, and US telephone companies such as Pacific
Telesis and Southwestern Bell.
Together they are providing the Pounds 2m in loans believed to be needed to
allow the channel to break even within three years.
Cable operators in turn will pay Pounds 1 a year for each subscriber, who
will receive The Parliamentary Channel automatically as part of the basic
package of channels.
This year the channel will concentrate on coverage of the Commons. It hopes
to add the Lords and parliamentary committees next year.
A three-hours-a-day digest of the proceedings of the European parliament in
Strasbourg should be available from September.
The Parliamentary Channel would like to be able to broadcast from the Marco
Polo satellite system launched by British Satellite Broadcasting - in which
Pearson, owner of the Financial Times, had a significant stake - when the
channel becomes available next year for public-service broadcasting uses.
Ironically, the only interruption to the flow of debate on The Parliamentary
Channel will come with the calling of a general election.
When politics moves outside the chamber, the channel will go off the air for
the six weeks of the campaign and will only come back when the MPs return to
the Commons from the hustings.
</TEXT>
